<subSubSection id="1C8A6552A531891C8CE74DB889DB37BA" pageId="47" pageNumber="320" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="542F36D9A531891C8CE74DB889DB37BA" blockId="47.[151,756,1161,1697]" pageId="47" pageNumber="320">
<emphasis id="66E4EACBA531891C8CE74DB888F235BA" bold="true" box="[151,254,1161,1185]" pageId="47" pageNumber="320">Remarks:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="93904D5AA531891C8D784DBB89AF35BA" baseAuthorityName="WARNCKE" baseAuthorityYear="1992" box="[264,419,1161,1185]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="320" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tephronotus">
<emphasis id="66E4EACBA531891C8D784DBB89AF35BA" box="[264,419,1161,1185]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="320">H. tephronotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is still exclusively known only from the 
<specimenCount id="4296FD50A531891C8C894D98897235DA" box="[249,382,1193,1217]" pageId="47" pageNumber="320" type="female">nine females</specimenCount>
of the original 
<typeStatus id="8B2B887BA531891C8E6E4D9B8A4035D9" box="[542,588,1194,1218]" pageId="47" pageNumber="320">type</typeStatus>
series; the male is unknown. The epithet is derived from τέφρα (Greek) and means “ash grey back”, as for example are back and wing covers of the Persian Nuthatch (
<taxonomicName id="93904D5AA531891C8E4A4C388AE9343A" authorityName="Sharpe" authorityYear="1872" box="[570,741,1289,1313]" class="Aves" family="Sittidae" genus="Sitta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="47" pageNumber="320" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tephronota">
<emphasis id="66E4EACBA531891C8E4A4C388AE9343A" box="[570,741,1289,1313]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="320">Sitta tephronota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The bee species in question is completely black. (Of course, scientific names do not necessarily have to agree with the facts.) 
<taxonomicName id="93904D5AA531891C8D484C588A07349A" baseAuthorityName="WARNCKE" baseAuthorityYear="1992" box="[312,523,1385,1409]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="320" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tephronotus">
<emphasis id="66E4EACBA531891C8D484C588A07349A" box="[312,523,1385,1409]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="320">Hylaeus tephronotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is clearly smaller than 
<taxonomicName id="93904D5AA531891C8CE74CBB891E34BA" baseAuthorityName="KIRBY" baseAuthorityYear="1802" box="[151,274,1417,1441]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="320" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dilatatus">
<emphasis id="66E4EACBA531891C8CE74CBB891E34BA" box="[151,274,1417,1441]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="320">H. dilatatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and resembles 
<taxonomicName id="93904D5AA531891C8DC84CBB8A3334BA" baseAuthorityName="Alfken" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[440,575,1417,1441]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="320" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pfankuchi">
<emphasis id="66E4EACBA531891C8DC84CBB8A3334BA" box="[440,575,1417,1441]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="320">H. pfankuchi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
not only because of missing side spots. Different appears to be the clear dense fine punctation of the metasomal terga. A peculiarity is the strikingly long bristles on the lower part of the clypeus. 
<taxonomicName id="93904D5AA531891C8D694F3B89B8373A" baseAuthorityName="WARNCKE" baseAuthorityYear="1992" box="[281,436,1545,1569]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="320" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tephronotus">
<emphasis id="66E4EACBA531891C8D694F3B89B8373A" box="[281,436,1545,1569]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="320">H. tephronotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been recorded as a mountain species from few sites (
<collectingRegion id="9654F83BA531891C8D964F188A4D375A" box="[486,577,1577,1601]" country="Turkey" name="Hakkari" pageId="47" pageNumber="320">Hakkâri</collectingRegion>
, 
<quantity id="93689B3CA531891C8E244F188AEB375A" box="[596,743,1577,1601]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="47" pageNumber="320" unit="m" value="2350.0" valueMax="3000.0" valueMin="1700.0">1700–3000 m</quantity>
), flying early in August. It is apparently a species of limited distribution, found only in 
<collectingCountry id="2C877649A531891C8DC74F588A0F379A" box="[439,515,1641,1665]" name="Turkey" pageId="47" pageNumber="320">Turkey</collectingCountry>
. It is rarely recorded in 
<collectingCountry id="2C877649A531891C8CE74FB888EE37BA" box="[151,226,1673,1697]" name="Turkey" pageId="47" pageNumber="320">Turkey</collectingCountry>
(1 province, 
<figureCitation id="CCAB2A5CA531891C8D1D4FB889C037BA" box="[365,460,1673,1697]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="68.[211,244,1429,1451]" captionTargetBox="[211,1414,859,1420]" captionTargetId="figure-259@68.[211,1414,859,1420]" captionTargetPageId="68" captionText="Fig. 17: Distribution map of rarely recorded Hylaeus species in Turkey: species collected in only one (1-12) or two (II-X)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742935" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742935/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="320">Fig. 17.8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
